					<h4>Western Book Roundup</h4>
		
		<h1>Write Your Letter to the President at the Boulder Book Store</h1>
		<h2><i></i></h2>
		<div class="text-feature_print">
							<p>By Jenny Shank, 2-18-09</p>
			
			
							<p>Artist <a target="_blank" href="http://www.ashleymaskharris.com/" title="Ashley Mask Harris">Ashley Mask Harris</a> will perform a piece entitled &#8220;Dear Mr. President&#8230;&#8221; at the Boulder Book Store on March 14 (12-4 p.m.).&nbsp; She&#8217;ll set up with a typewriter and transcribe any message that passersby wish to send President Obama, then mail all the letters to the White House, &#8220;using the age-old tradition of letter-writing as the physical manifestation of American democracy.&#8221;  Several of Ms. Mask Harris&#8217;s friends will perform the same feat simultaneously in locations across the country.
</p>
<p>
The University of Idaho sent word that Creative Writing Professor Kim Barnes has sold her third novel to Alfred A. Knopf.&nbsp; The book will be called <I>American Mecca</I>.
</p>
<p>
I discussed this novel-in-progress with Ms. Barnes when I<a target="_blank" href=" http://www.newwest.net/topic/article/an_interview_with_kim_barnes_part_two/C39/L39/" title=" interviewed her a few months ago"> interviewed her a few months ago</a> about her novel <I>A Country Called Home</I>.&nbsp; She said the forthcoming book is based on the experiences of her aunt and uncle, who took a job as a derrick foreman in an oilfield in Saudi Arabia.
</p>
<p>
According to a press release about the new book: 
</p>
<blockquote><p>&#8220;The story is set in the 1960s in a gated compound of the Arabian American Oil Company (Aramco), where the couple takes up residence in a seemingly utopian society as adopted members of the Aramco &#8216;family.&#8217; The corporate family is comprised of largely American and European professionals and Arab, Pakistani, Indonesian, Indian, Italian and Spanish laborers. As they occupy a new life of unprecedented luxury, the narrator&#8217;s husband is accused of killing a young Arabian woman. That tragedy, and the intrigue surrounding it, take place in a time of political and social upheaval in Saudi Arabia, when definitive features of an idealized American culture, transported to a foreign desert, collide with centuries-old values.&#8221;
<br />
</p></blockquote>
<p>
Barnes will share her writing process with her students at the University of Idaho. &#8220;Because I&#8217;ve placed this book on proposal, I&#8217;m just in the beginning stages of discovering and developing my characters inside this story,&#8221; Barnes said. &#8220;I have months and months of research, writing and revision ahead of me. Inviting my students to observe my process teaches them that writing is not about magic and immediate gratification &#8211; it&#8217;s about learning the craft and trusting the process. Writing is not a hobby or even a job &#8211; it&#8217;s a discipline that I will practice every day for the rest of my life. This may be the most important thing that we can teach our students.&#8221;
</p>
<p>
According to <a target="_blank" href=" http://www.coloradoan.com/article/20090210/OPINION01/902100310/1014/OPINION" title="the Coloradoan">the Coloradoan</a>, Jane Tester, the owner of The Old Corner Book Shop in Fort Collins, closed the store Friday because of her recent stroke, but hopes to find a buyer for the store, a 50-year-old shop which she purchased in 1975.&nbsp; (Via <a target="_blank" href="http://news.shelf-awareness.com/nview.jsp?appid=411&amp;j=626701" title="Shelf Awareness">Shelf Awareness</a>.)
</p>
<p>
Have some regional book news or events to share?&nbsp; Please <script type="text/javascript">
